name "sec:Attacks"

\end_inset

Attacks on TLS
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This section lists the attacks that motivated the current recommendations.
 This is not intended to be an extensive survey of TLS's security.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While there are widely deployed mitigations for some of the attacks listed
 below, we believe that their root causes necessitate a more systemic solution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
BEAST
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The BEAST attack 
\begin_inset Flex EntityXRef
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
BEAST
\end_layout

\end_inset

 uses issues with the TLS 1.0 implementation of CBC (that is, the predictable
 initialization vector) to decrypt parts of a packet, and specifically shows
 how this can be used to decrypt HTTP cookies when run over TLS.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Lucky Thirteen
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A consequence of the MAC-then-encrypt design in all current versions of
 TLS is the existence of padding oracle attacks 
\begin_inset Flex EntityXRef
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Padding-Oracle
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 A recent incarnation of these attacks is the Lucky Thirteen attack 
\begin_inset Flex EntityXRef
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
CBC-Attack
\end_layout

\end_inset

, a timing side-channel attack that allows the attacker to decrypt arbitrary
 ciphertext.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Attacks on RC4
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The RC4 algorithm 
\begin_inset Flex EntityXRef
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
RC4
\end_layout

\end_inset

 has been used with TLS (and previously, SSL) for many years.
 Attacks have also been known for a long time, e.g.
 
\begin_inset Flex EntityXRef
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
RC4-Attack-FMS
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 But recent attacks (
\begin_inset Flex EntityXRef
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
RC4-Attack
\end_layout

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Flex EntityXRef
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
RC4-Attack-AlF
\end_layout

\end_inset

) have weakened this algorithm even more.
 See 
\begin_inset Flex EntityXRef
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
I-D.popov-tls-prohibiting-rc4
\end_layout

\end_inset

 for more details.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Compression Attacks: CRIME and BREACH
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The CRIME attack 
\begin_inset Flex EntityXRef
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
CRIME
\end_layout

\end_inset

 allows an active attacker to decrypt cyphertext (specifically, cookies)
 when TLS is used with protocol-level compression.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The BREACH attack 
\begin_inset Flex EntityXRef
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
BREACH
\end_layout

\end_inset

 makes similar use of HTTP-level compression to decrypt secret data passed
 in the HTTP response.
 We note that compression of the HTTP message body is much more prevalent
 than compression at the TLS level.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The former attack can be mitigated by disabling TLS compression, as recommended
 below.
 We are not aware of mitigations at the protocol level to the latter attack,
 and so application-level mitigations are needed (see 
\begin_inset Flex EntityXRef
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
BREACH
\end_layout

\end_inset

).
 For example, implementations of HTTP that use CSRF tokens will need to
 randomize them even when the recommendations of [XXX] are adopted.
\end_layout

